  "narrative": {
    "aboutMe": "NASA JPL Software Engineer with 6 years of experience who blends exceptional skills across leadership, communication, and technical domains. Has written code to run on Mars, designed the cloud infrastructure scientists use to explore data from Jupiter, and developed visualizations Presidents rely on to watch robots land on another planet.\n\nPassionate about science, philosophy, and academic pursuits. A very cerebral person who thinks very deeply about problems. An exceptional oral and written communicator. Extremely well equipped to translate complex technical topics to simple, easy to understand concepts. A very good teacher.\n\nGrew up in Oakland, CA. Loves the outdoors, hiking, biking, SCUBA. A huge tinkerer. Has taken woodworking classes. Very handy and repairs things around the house constantly. Has done light electrical, carpentry, drywall, and painting work. Has a workshop in garage that was built and organized myself. Really want to get a table saw and miter saw but don't have the space for it.\n\nReally into electronics, computers, and software. Has done multiple projects with Raspberry Pis and Arduinos. Has a home server with a ton of self-hosted free and open-source software. Loves writing code.\n\nCreated this automated AI job application assistant tool. You provide a simple list of job URLs to an agent, the agent then scrapes the job and company info, the agent then reads my personal information and background and writes custom tailored resumes and cover letters for each job posting. Each resume and cover letter have multiple professional templates to choose from. This was built from a combination of free and open-source software on GitHub, OpenCode, and stuff I did myself.",
    "whatLookingFor": "Want to achieve a career adjustment. About at mid-stage in career. I miss feeling passionate about my work. I was passionate at JPL but at my current role in the private sector at Optimal Dynamics I'm uninspired. My dream job is building the software and hardware systems used by scientists to investigate and explore other worlds and managing the engineering teams that do that important work. I want to get closer to that goal in several ways: - Non-profit and/or academic organization - Publicly funded organization - Work in the service of science - Work in flight software preferably, but I'd also go back to ground data systems - Do NOT want to work on defense or military infrastructure - Want to work on climate, science, exploration, robotics. I have very limited flight software experience. Practically no embedded systems experience. I would take a junior level flight software role, despite the fact that it would be a paycut and a less senior role.",
    "tonePreferences": [
      "Confident but not arrogant",
      "Specific with numbers and impact",
      "Avoid buzzwords like 'synergy' or 'leverage'"
    ],
    "keyAchievements": [
      "Worked on flight software for the Mars Sample Return project for 1 year at NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory",
      "Integrated telemetry data by connecting AMPCS to an Entry Descent and Landing (EDL) visualization for the Mars 2020 Perseverance landing. People all around the world watched our visualization when we successfully landed on Mars on February 18th, 2021. American President Joe Biden tweeted a picture of himself watching our visualization on landing day. French President Emanuel Macron also tweeted a picture of him watching our visualization. The team that developed the visualization was 7 people including me. I added the orbiter telemetry data so on landing day we could show the actual positions of Mars Reconnaissance Orbiter and MAVEN.",
      "Developed the Cloud Ground Data Systems infrastructure and software for the Europa Clipper project that launched to Jupiter successfully on October 14th, 2024.",
      "Lead the GDS team for a multi-mission subsystem that supported 12 active flight projects."
    ]
  }
}